<div id="review_2504196744" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2504196744" />
    <a title="Steven Godin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26706841-steven-godin"><img alt="Steven Godin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621019440p2/26706841.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2504196744?book_show_action=true">Aug 23, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steven Godin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steven Godin" href="/user/show/26706841-steven-godin">Steven Godin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26706841-steven-godin?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26706841-steven-godin?shelf=latin-america">latin-america</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2504196744" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3836006534749537926">Since 1973, Bolaño has lived outside Chile and most of his fiction has reflected that. His previous novel, The Savage Detectives was a work as peripatetic as his own existence. He himself was clearly a little underwhelmed by the contemporary Chilean scene, and perhaps with good reason. By Night in Chile, for me anyway, is not a typical Bolaño novel, thus I didn&apos;t like it as much when thinking of 2666, The Savage Detectives, and the brilliant collection of short-stories in Last Evenings on Earth.</span>
  <span id="freeText3836006534749537926" style="display:none">Since 1973, Bolaño has lived outside Chile and most of his fiction has reflected that. His previous novel, The Savage Detectives was a work as peripatetic as his own existence. He himself was clearly a little underwhelmed by the contemporary Chilean scene, and perhaps with good reason. By Night in Chile, for me anyway, is not a typical Bolaño novel, thus I didn't like it as much when thinking of 2666, The Savage Detectives, and the brilliant collection of short-stories in Last Evenings on Earth. Nevertheless, as a Bolaño fan it was still worth reading, and it felt like writer who had an enviable control over every heartbeat, every change in tempo, and every dazzling image. His prose was constantly challenging, at times lyrical, allusive, and filled with a biting wit. <br /><br />The story concerns Father Sebastian Urrutia, who is dying (or at least he believes he is dying) where over a single night, with sometimes querulous voice and not entirely reliable memory - he revisits scenes from his life as a failed poet but eminent literary critic. And through the character of Urrutia, Bolaño produces a satirical analysis of Chilean literature, and the politically contaminated soil out of which it emerged. Urrutia is a member of Opus Dei, and repelled by everyday humanity, twisted by the semi-repression of his homosexuality, and tormented about his shortcomings by an engimatic shadow figure. Since this is the memoirs of a very old man, who has a long tale to relate, its short length didn't help, with the first half of the novel a bit of a struggle that will likely effect non-Latin American readers more.<br /><br />Essentially written in one paragraph, the riveting stream of consciousness makes for an intriguing look into the connection between literature and politics during the time of Pinochet, but I felt it never had the power of previously read Bolaño. 3.5/5</span>
  <a data-text-id="3836006534749537926" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


