<div id="review_2607174091" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2607174091" />
    <a title="Read By RodKelly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43107057-read-by-rodkelly"><img alt="Read By RodKelly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609358692p2/43107057.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2607174091?book_show_action=true">Jan 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Read By RodKelly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Read By RodKelly" href="/user/show/43107057-read-by-rodkelly">Read By RodKelly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/29857703-by-night-in-chile">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2607174091" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer273644697680695677">I&apos;m in love. Bolaño is a genius, a wizard, a paragon of writers, master of constructing the essence of people and places, stacking details that build toward a sensation that is at once hallucinatory and bizarre, lucid and sublime.<br/><br/>Father Sebastián Urrutia Lacroix is on his deathbed in the throes of a dementia-fueled episode, confessing outloud (or in his head), fluidly moving through various snapshots of his life, of which the most memorable are those that fill the dying priest with insuperable g</span>
  <span id="freeText273644697680695677" style="display:none">I'm in love. Bolaño is a genius, a wizard, a paragon of writers, master of constructing the essence of people and places, stacking details that build toward a sensation that is at once hallucinatory and bizarre, lucid and sublime.<br /><br />Father Sebastián Urrutia Lacroix is on his deathbed in the throes of a dementia-fueled episode, confessing outloud (or in his head), fluidly moving through various snapshots of his life, of which the most memorable are those that fill the dying priest with insuperable guilt. Written in one unbroken paragraph over 120 pages, Bolaño's prose snakes along, presenting the scenes of the father's life as one horror-tinged episode after another. Unpredictable and striking imagery pervades this text; metaphors in one episode vaguely hint at what will come later. The writing is poetic and slightly baroque, sentences serpentine and unconcerned with chronology of events. Bolaño's favorite themes seem to be fate and the futility of fighting against it, as well as the ephemeral quality of everything, the immeasurability of time and the banality of the human existence within it. <br /><br />By the end and throughout, the senile father is unsure if the events he's confessing happen 2 days or 10 years ago, and the novel begs the question: would it even matter? could anything be in our lives be different regardless of the the choices we make? Is there a solution for anything, or are we just resigned to our fate?</span>
  <a data-text-id="273644697680695677" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


