  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2795518971" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2795518971" />
    <a title="Katia N" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7381993-katia-n"><img alt="Katia N" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1370960553p2/7381993.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2795518971?book_show_action=true">Apr 26, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katia N" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katia N" href="/user/show/7381993-katia-n">Katia N</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2795518971" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17713451375082834142">Bolano was saying &quot;I write to remember the past stories, laugh at them or turn them into the different stories, inventing the new end&quot;. And it is so true for all his books I&apos;ve read so far. He is a poet in everything he writes. And he writes mainly about other writers, poets, literary critics. He also adheres to the tradition, called by a fashionable word &quot;intertextuality&quot; of mentioning and discussing other books and blurring the artificial division between fiction and non-fiction (This traditio</span>
  <span id="freeText17713451375082834142" style="display:none">Bolano was saying "I write to remember the past stories, laugh at them or turn them into the different stories, inventing the new end". And it is so true for all his books I've read so far. He is a poet in everything he writes. And he writes mainly about other writers, poets, literary critics. He also adheres to the tradition, called by a fashionable word "intertextuality" of mentioning and discussing other books and blurring the artificial division between fiction and non-fiction (This tradition has got deep roots in Spanish language literature. It might be traced all the way to Don Quixote, but more recently it is very visible in the modern Latin American Literature starting from Borges, the Argentinians, and all the way to Zambra and Luisseli). <br /><br />The novel is devoted to the darkest times in recent Chilean history - the time of the dictatorship. The narrator is an old padre who is a literary schooler as well. Through his eyes, we experience the biggest power of any dictatorship - the power of sticky fear which would stop a human being thinking about the morality of his choices. Padre, or rather Bolano also tells a lot stories and possibly changes the endings. But there is one story there for which Bolano did not change much.<br /><br />This is the story of an aspiring writer and her charming american husband. To boost her literary career, she hosts an intellectual saloon in her house. While downstairs in the basement her husband and his colleagues are busy with something much less innocent. This is the true story of <a href="https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/world/article24494053.html" rel="nofollow noopener">Mariana Callejas and Michael Townley</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17713451375082834142" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

